Cornerstones of Civilization 6: E is for Economy The second to last letter in the SPICE(R) series is upon us. E for economics. Once again we have the two subcategories from the first two letters: organization and interaction. When it comes to economic organization it is helpful to look at current economic systems and pull what you know or have experienced from them. Important questions to ask yourself are: Who is at the top? Who has control over money? What makes up the foundation of this system? How do people move up and down on the ladder? How does the government fit into this system? Interaction is just as simple. It consists of how people interact with the economy and vice versa as well as how that economy interacts with the environment and other economies. Things to keep in mind: taxes, resource depletion, trade doctrine, relevant exports and imports, etc.. This process and the historical moments that led to it, as well as the effects of #militarization on the Isla Nena, have been documented through different cinematographic works made in and outside of #PuertoRico. Short #films, medium-length films and feature films, as well as #archives, are a source of #memory of one of the most important historical events in the defense of human and environmental rights, as well as against militarization and in favor of #peace, in our country and the region. On the occasion of the commemoration of 20 years since the cease of the bombing and still in the face of broad demands for fundamental rights and reparations for the people of Vieques, the Vieques #Film and #HumanRights #Festival (#FCDHV) has brought together some of these #documentary works, which can be accessed for #free #online.

Are you getting all you can out of your film festival run? ü§∑üèæ‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è We‚Äôve been to a fair share of festivals of all sizes but honestly can‚Äôt make really good use of any festival if you don‚Äôt know what your end goal is. ‚ùìDo you want to connect with other like minded filmmakers?  Or ‚ùìDo you want meet potential distributors or industry veterans?  Once you clarify your goal it will be much easier to prepare but in case you don‚Äôt know. Here are some tips for all three. ü§ù CONNECT WITH FILMMAKERS ‚ö´Ô∏èPrepare to get up early and stay out late.  You can find filmmakers everywhere espcially at big festivals like the Sidewalk Film Festival (Shown above) You‚Äôll likely meet other creatives at: - The host hotel - Filmmakers brunches - Opening night movie screenings. - Workshops - After parties - Award shows Some events start at 10am and some end at 4am. So get rest. Also organize your contact list. Have a system on how you want to exchange information and how you will remember people. Swapping instagrams usually works well. But get an email or phone number of the people you REALLY want to follow up with.  üé¨ MEET INDUSTRY VETERANS ‚ö´Ô∏è Do your research, be prepared. If you see an event that is sponsored by HBO, A&E, Netflix etc. Plan to be there on time and stay afterwards. Sometimes and I really mean sometimes, these companies send representatives out for the event.  Research who will be there and think what can I offer them.  ‚ùìDo you have a slate of films they might be interested in?  ‚ùìCan you strike a conversation and invite them to lunch?  Don‚Äôt be the desperate creative begging for a shot. Be the savvy producer offering them an opportunity.  Make sure you get THEIR CONTACT information. If you‚Äôve got a post card or visual of your film give it to them. They might throw it away but at least you build some name recognition so they‚Äôll be a reminder when you follow up once the festival is over.  Finally, have fun. Festivals are meant to celebrate your hard work and help you move forward.
